        output='Based on the provided S-1 prospectus excerpts, here is a detailed breakdown of Starlink’s network capacity, satellite constellation size, subscriber count, and utilization/performance metrics as of the reporting period (primarily Q1 2026 and full-year 2025).\n\n### 1. Satellite Constellation Size & Scale\n*   **Total Satellites in Orbit:** As of March 31, 2026, Starlink operated approximately **9,600 broadband and mobile satellites** in Low-Earth Orbit (LEO).\n*   **Market Dominance:** This constellation accounted for approximately **75% of all active maneuverable satellites** in orbit globally.\n*   **Launch Cadence:** In 2025 alone, SpaceX launched approximately **3,100 Starlink satellites**, which is roughly five times the total number of active satellites in the world\'s second-largest LEO constellation.\n*   **Mobile Constellation:** The dedicated satellite-to-mobile constellation grew from ~360 V1 Mobile satellites in January 2025 to approximately **650 V1 Mobile satellites** by March 31, 2026.\n*   **Regulatory Authorizations:** The company has authorization to deploy 7,500 satellites (including operations in the 2GHz spectrum band).\n\n### 2. Network Capacity & Next-Generation Expansion\n*   **Current Capacity:** The current constellation of ~9,600 satellites supports over **700 Tbps of cumulative downlink capacity**.\n*   **Next-Gen V3 Broadband Satellites:** \n    *   Designed to offer **1 Tbps of downlink capacity per satellite**.\n    *   Deployment begins in the second half of 2026 using the Starship launch vehicle.\n    *   A single Starship launch will deploy up to **60 V3 satellites**, representing a **20-fold increase** in downlink capacity deployed per launch compared to Falcon 9, drastically lowering expansion costs.\n*   **Next-Gen Mobile (Gen2) & Spectrum Acquisition:** \n    *   SpaceX entered a **$19.6 billion** equity and cash agreement to acquire 65 MHz of U.S. spectrum and global Mobile Satellite Service spectrum licenses from EchoStar (expected to close in November 2027).\n    *   Combined with V2 Mobile satellites (planned for 2027) and optimized 5G protocols, this will increase mobile capacity by **orders of magnitude** compared to the first-generation constellation, aiming to eliminate mobile "dead zones" and support broadband data/IoT for unmodified cell phones.\n\n### 3. Subscriber Count & Market Reach\n*   **Total Starlink Subscribers:** Reached **10.3 million** as of March 31, 2026, representing a **105% year-over-year increase** (up from 5.0 million in Q1 2025). \n    *   *Note:* This metric includes Personal (Residential, Roam) and Business plans but *excludes* managed enterprise and government contracts.\n*   **Global Footprint:** Subscribers are spread across **164 countries, territories, and markets**, collectively home to over 3.3 billion people.\n*   **Satellite-to-Mobile Users:** Provides texting, data, and over-the-top (OTT) voice services to approximately **7.4 million monthly unique devices** across ~30 countries, in partnership with over 30 mobile network operators (MNOs).\n*   **Enterprise & Government:** Serves major enterprise clients (e.g., United Airlines, Carnival, Maersk, John Deere) across aviation, maritime, agriculture, and retail, often transitioning from a backup network to the primary critical infrastructure provider.\n\n### 4. Utilization, Performance & Financial Metrics\n**Network Performance:**\n*   **Latency:** Median latency is approximately **25 milliseconds** (with round-trip latencies as low as 21 ms), rivaling terrestrial broadband and supporting real-time gaming and video calls.\n*   **Download Speeds:** Median peak-hour download speeds for residential users are **225 Mbps**, with the network capable of delivering speeds exceeding **400 Mbps**.\n\n**Subscriber ARPU (Average Revenue Per User):**\n*   **Q1 2026:** $66 / month\n*   **Q1 2025:** $86 / month\n*   **FY 2025:** $81 / month\n*   **FY 2024:** $91 / month\n*   **FY 2023:** $99 / month\n*   *Strategic Context:* The deliberate decline in ARPU is a byproduct of the company\'s strategy to prioritize global scale, market access, and operational efficiency over maximizing per-user revenue. As the subscriber base expands outside of North America into emerging markets, the blended ARPU naturally decreases.\n\n**Connectivity Segment Financials (Starlink):**\n*   **Segment Income from Operations:** \n    *   Q1 2026: **$1.18 billion** (vs. $1.03B in Q1 2025)\n    *   FY 2025: **$4.42 billion** (vs. $2.00B in FY 2024)\n*   **Segment Adjusted EBITDA:** \n    *   Q1 2026: **$2.08 billion** (vs. $1.61B in Q1 2025)\n    *   FY 2025: **$7.16 billion** (vs. $3.84B in FY 2024)\n*   *Profitability Trend:* Starlink has achieved massive margin expansion and robust cash flow generation, driven by the high fixed-cost/low marginal-cost nature of the satellite network and the rapid scaling of the subscriber base.',
